U.S Garand Springfield: SN. 5809XXX : Original National Match II  
Receiver Drawing numbers F 6528291 heat no. Z6A (NM-II Receivers were the first Garand receivers made especially for the National Matches.
Barrel No. SA F6525448 and marked with large S (for Sighted), T (for Targeted), small m (For Match) and P (for Proof). All most other parts also have NM part numbers. 
Note: Parts were not stamped with the "NM" designation since this practice started in 1957. production of NM parts ended soon after.
Rear sight: Small aperture. Front  (None hooded) are NM. Front sight is stamped NM 0.62
None military parts installed: 1. Holbrook device. This device prevents bolt from slamming on your thumb and spent clips "flying" out and getting damaged or dirty. 2.  Gas cylinder pressure regulator plug, to keep the rifle from getting damaged from hammering on the ejection cycle. Newer types of ammunitions are more powerful and not designed for the Garand gas system. 
All original parts are included and can be changed with no problem, if your familiar with the Garand. . plus you get all Garand cleaning gear and tools. Bore is in excellent  condition with no pitting. Rifle shows normal handling wear. Stock is in excellent condition.

The National Match grade of Rifles were built for better accuracy and machined to closer tolerances, then the standard issue rifle. All parts were also made to higher tolerance specifications.

See:( http://www.americanrifleman.org/articles/national-match-m1 ) For more information.
Stock is not glassed. Glass bedding did not start until 1957-58. Up to that point stock were selected for a tighter fit with no flaws.

When Glocks showed up in West Tennessee 30 years ago, we didn’t think any of us could hit anything with such a pistol. We were wrong. Here is a Glock that takes that now-famous accuracy up a couple notches, the 17C Compensated and Ported variant. This is a pistol you can shoot all day long and never tire of. Manufacturer is Glock Ges.m.b.H., of Deutsch-Wagram, Austria. Importer is Glock Inc. of Smyrna, Georgia. Construction is steel barrel, slide, and internal parts in a steel impregnated polymer frame. Type is double action only blowback action, striker fired semi-auto pistol. Caliber is 9mm Parabellum, 9mm Luger, 9x19, call it what you will, THE 9mm. Barrel is 6 groove, 1:9.84 twist 4.02 inch, with dual 3/8 inch ports positioned at 11 and 1 o’clock 1 1/4 inches back of the muzzle to eliminate barrel rise, dissipate heat, increase accuracy, and virtually eliminate felt recoil. Slide is ported as well, as the photos show. Sights are stake on white dot front and dovetailed U shaped white outline rear. Trigger is .400 smooth face combat type, but with Glock Trigger Safety that augments the firing pin and drop safeties. Glocks do NOT have magazine safeties; that is, they will fire single shot with no magazine. Trigger pull is a smooth consistent 5 pounds. Finish is black matte. Weight empty is 23 ounces. The Generation 3 frame has an integral single slot Picatinny accessory rail, textured interval finger groove front strap, stippled surface laterals, and checkered serration back strap surface. Sight radius is 6 1/4 inches; height is 5 3/8 inches from the top of the rear sight to the magazine floorplate, slide thickness is 1.05 with frame thickness of 1.17. Overall length is 7 3/8 inches from the muzzle to the top of the grip frame strut. postcontent:
I have 80 rounds of Buffalo Bore 158gr 38 SPL+P rounds for sale. These rounds are less than three months old and have been kept in a dehumidified / climate-controlled home. I sold my .38 and no longer have use for these rounds. The two MTM cases are included. I didn't keep the original boxes, only the flap. Must be 21+ and able to pick up. Thanks for looking!


The new Buffalo Bore Heavy 38 SPL+p ammo will maximize the effectiveness of your 38 SPL revolver. The powders are flash suppressed so as to not hinder your vision should you be required to drop the hammer in low light.

Item 20A/20 is the terrific SOFT lead semi wad cutter hollow cavity bullet, however we've added a gas check to stop the leading that this load typically causes with other manufacturers version of this bullet.

Item 20B/20 uses the low velocity (LV) Jacketed Hollow Point bullet that is designed to expand at as little as 800 fps, so you will get expansion out of very short barrels.

Whether you prefer the very soft semi wadcutter lead bullet, or a very soft JHC, (jacketed hollow cavity) these HVY 38 SPL+p loads will turbo charge your 38 SPL revolver.

The tactical reload: Short (2 to 2.5 inch) barreled revolvers have short ejectors. Those short ejectors typically used on 2 inch to 2.5 inch barreled revolvers are not long enough to fully eject 357 magnum brass. So if you are forced into a situation where you need to reload your weapon under fire, you will find yourself picking your fired/empty 357 brass out of the cylinder one at a time - this is very bad. On the other hand, 38SPL brass is shorter than 357 brass and those short ejectors will often fully eject 38SPL brass. We have experimented a great deal with short barreled revolvers and have found that 38SPL brass normally offers an advantage if you need to reload your "snub nose" revolver, in a hurry.

Check out the below velocities that I fired from my personal revolvers. We believe that real world, stock, "over the counter" guns, give real world results, so we don't advertise velocities that are fired from long test barrels.

These 38SPL+P loads are generating low-end 357 magnum, ballistics. If you have an older or more fragile 38SPL, or if you are recoil sensitive, consider using our HVY Standard Pressure 38SPL ammunition. It is safe to be fired in any 38SPL revolver and it still packs much more punch than ordinary 38SPL ammo.

Item 20A: 158gr., very soft cast, semi wad cutter, (Keith) hollow cavity, with a gas check. This bullet will mushroom violently on impact and will penetrate roughly 14 inches in human flesh. Again, this bullet is gas checked and will not lead your barrel.

title: For Sale:  Para Carry 9 LDA
postcontent:
Para Carry 9 LDA.  Includes 1 original 8-round mag, three Para new current design flush 7-round mags, a plastic Para box and a hardcopy of a downloaded instruction manual. 

This pistol was made in Canada in August 2008.  I bought it used six months ago.  The finish is Para's Covert Black and is in average to above average condition with apparent holster wear.  It has a front Tritium night sight with good brightness.

Para is famous for their exclusive LDA (light double-action) trigger design.  It is as sweet as you will find.  The design allows you to carry more safely as the bobbed hammer rests in a half-cocked condition.  When the safeties are disengaged (grip safety and thumb safety) a light double-action pull completes cocking and fires the pistol.  The light trigger and match-grade bull barrel permit great accuracy and very tight groups.

The pistol feels good in the hand and recoil is minimal.  The size is excellent for concealed carry.

1. ADJUSTABLE SIGHTS
The front and rear sights are removable GLOCK style sights. The rear sight is adjustable for both windage and elevation.

2. LAST ROUND LOCK OPEN
The slide will lock open after the last round in the magazine has been fired. Our unique patented magazine design and heat-treated steel lock open insert allows us to offer this special and desirable feature which you can only find on 'Advantage Arms' .22LR Conversion Kits for the GLOCK pistol.

3. INTERNAL FIRING PIN SAFETY
Glock incorporated an internal firing pin safety into their guns. We thought it was important enough to include it on our conversion kits as well. Our internal firing pin safety is designed to eliminate accidental discharges from dropping the firearm.

Installation is simple and does not require any modifications to your GLOCK pistol. Simply remove the GLOCK magazine and slide as outlined in your GLOCK owner's manual. postcontent:
I used to be the team mechanic in Albuquerque and played every weekend. After moving to Colorado, I wanted to play again but with school and work, I never could find the time to do so. I have one more semester left and a little tight on cash, so here goes my getting out of the hobby sale. All prices are negotiable, make an offer. I need everything gone.

1. Stock Tokyo Marui Sig 552. I bought this from an old friend who bought it brand new at the hobby shop he worked at. I took it to 2 games and if worked flawlessly. Comes with the small NiCd battery I got with the gun (doesn't really hold a charge. it will shoot for about 1 and a half mag fulls before dying). Does not have the orange tip. I'm not sure if my friend removed it or if it never came with it (this does not have any of the markings scratched off so it may actually be that old). No box/paperwork, no charger, comes with 2 stock mid caps (43rd) and 1 hi cap magazine. These are going for $265 at redwolf. Asking $150

2. Stock Tokyo Marui M1A1 Thompson. Pretty much the same story as above except I never took this to a game. It does shoot very well. Only problem with this one is that semi auto works intermittently due to the cam being worn on the sector gear. No box/paperwork, no charger, comes with 1 mid cap (60rd) magazine and a large NiCd battery (same as above, doesn't really hold a charge but you can use it to check function). These are going for $375 at redwolf. Asking $225

3. Highly modified Echo1 P90 and another for parts. The normal looking one in the box is a highly modified, high speed P90. It shoots around 40 rounds per second at about 330 feet per second. Has an AWS mosfet installed with deans plug. Set up for a 3 cell lipo. Angle of engagement adjusted, sorbothane installed, short stroked SHS piston and gearset driven by a high speed motor. The other P90 with the long barrel was a high power project that I never finished. I have enough parts to put it back to stock form and get it working but just do not have the time. You could use it for parts or rebuild it. Comes with one box, 4 mid cap mags, 1 box mag with short M4 hi cap mag, factory charger (will not work though since both guns are wired to deans). Asking $350

4. Stock CYMA CM122 "Sig P226" AEP. You may laugh at these but in cold weather games, gas pistols just don't work well enough. The charger has been modified to be plugged into a hobby charger with deans plug. Comes with box/paperwork, bag of bbs, cleaning/unjamming rod, one mag, one battery, and charging adapter. 5. bunch of parts. Please note the plastic bin in the picture will not be included. Lots of pistons, springs, o-rings, motor connectors, hop up buckings, nubs, shims, etc. A lot of the parts in here are for the Echo1 P90 so I would like to sell this with the P90s unless somebody just wants the parts. 6. Not in the pictures, airsoft gear. I have a Pantech drop leg molle rig, drop leg universal holster, dump pouch, and a belt all in Pantech tan color (although to me it really looks somewhere in the middle between FDE and OD green). I also have a JT full mask with a small fan and push button switch mounted for defogging (the lens kept fogging up during indoor games. I did this mod before JT came out with their defogging unit). All sold except mask.
